This report synthesizes findings on how crime affects individuals across mental health, physical health, and socio-economic status. Crime significantly impacts mental health, leading to increases in anxiety, depression, and PTSD among victims. Physically, crime exposure results in injuries and psychological distress, impacting overall well-being. Socio-economically, crime correlates with lower income and higher victimization rates, especially in low-income neighborhoods. Community-wide, crime increases collective trauma, reducing social cohesion and engagement. Recommendations emphasize holistic approaches to address these interconnected issues and develop effective interventions.